.TH SECURE-SUDOERS 1 "March 2026" "secure-sudoers 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
secure-sudoers \- A memory-safe, high-security gatekeeper for sudo
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B secure-sudoers
[\fITOOL\fR] [\fIARGS\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B secure-sudoers
is a security-hardened delegation tool designed to be used as a replacement for direct sudo access. It enforces strict JSON-defined policies, isolates processes using Linux namespaces, and prevents TOCTOU (Time-of-Check to Time-of-Use) attacks.
.PP
The tool is strictly Linux-only and relies on kernel features like namespaces and capability dropping to ensure that even if a delegated tool is compromised, the impact on the host system is minimized.
.SH INVOCATION
The tool supports two invocation styles:
.TP
.B 1. Symlink Invocation
When invoked via a symlink (e.g., \fI/usr/local/bin/apt\fR -> \fI/usr/local/bin/secure-sudoers\fR), it uses the symlink's name as the tool to look up in the policy. This allows for a transparent user experience where delegated tools can be run normally.
.TP
.B 2. Direct Invocation
When invoked directly as \fBsecure-sudoers\fR, the first argument is treated as the tool name, and subsequent arguments are passed to that tool after validation.
.SH POLICY FORMAT
The central policy is a JSON file, typically located at \fI/etc/secure-sudoers/policy.json\fR.
.SS Global Settings
.TP
.B log_destination
"syslog" or "stdout".
.TP
.B admin_contact
A message to display to users when access is denied.
.TP
.B safe_arg_regex
A regex that all positional arguments must match unless they are specifically validated as paths.
.TP
.B blocked_paths
A list of absolute paths that are blocked globally (e.g., /etc/shadow, /root).
.TP
.B unauthorized_audit_mode
Determines how arguments are logged for unauthorized tools.
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\fBminimal\fR (default): Logs only the count of arguments (e.g., "[3 arguments suppressed]").
.IP \(bu 2
\fBkeys_only\fR: Logs flag names but redacts their values and all positional arguments.
.IP \(bu 2
\fBfull\fR: Logs all raw arguments in the clear.
.RE
.SS Tool Policies
Each tool entry defines:
.TP
.B real_binary
The absolute path to the actual binary to execute.
.TP
.B verbs
A list of allowed subcommands (e.g., "install", "update").
.TP
.B sensitive_flags
A list of flags whose arguments should always be redacted in logs (e.g., "--password").
.TP
.B flags
Allowed simple flags (e.g., "-y", "--quiet").
.TP
.B flags_with_args
Flags that require a simple string argument.
.TP
.B flags_with_path_args
Flags that require a path argument (subject to \fBblocked_paths\fR checks).
.TP
.B flag_rules
Complex rules for flag arguments (regex, list of constants, or combined).
.TP
.B isolation
Namespace and mount settings specific to this tool.
.SH SECURITY
.TP
.B 1. Signature Verification
The policy file MUST have a valid detached Ed25519 signature at \fIPOLICY_PATH.sig\fR. The signature is verified against the public key at \fI/etc/secure-sudoers/secure_sudoers_public_key.pem\fR.
.TP
.B 2. Namespace Isolation
Child processes are unshared from the host namespaces (Mount, Network, PID, IPC, UTS) as configured in the policy.
.TP
.B 3. Capability Dropping
All "dangerous" Linux capabilities (e.g., CAP_SYS_ADMIN, CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE) are dropped before the binary is executed via \fBfexecve\fR(2).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SECURE_SUDOERS_POLICY_PATH
Override the default policy location. Only available in debug builds.
.TP
.B SUDO_USER
Used for audit logging to identify the original user who invoked the tool.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 1
Fatal error (e.g., policy load failure, access denied, security violation).
.TP
.B 0 or Tool Exit Code
The exit code returned by the executed tool on success or failure.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/secure-sudoers/policy.json
The central security policy.
.TP
.I /etc/secure-sudoers/policy.json.sig
The Ed25519 signature for the policy.
.TP
.I /etc/secure-sudoers/secure_sudoers_public_key.pem
The public key used for verification.
.SH AUTHOR
Thomas Shephard
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR secure-sudoers-utils (1),
.BR sudo (8)
